  "mechanism": {
    "finding": "At margin=6 all 5 required_slot_margin fires happen at frame_depth==0 (fresh top-level statement, no component frame open), 3 of 5 flipping the argmax away from a real component candidate (+Image, +Callout) or a literal (LIT_STR) to a bare slot token -- the model front-loads all 5 required slots into degenerate one-token 'name = @N' statements in the first 5 decode positions, before any real component tree exists. The lever then goes permanently silent (every slot is 'filled' in the prefix) for the remaining ~150 tokens of decode, which do build a plausible Callout/Card/Card/Stack/Button tree -- but whichever statement is serialized as 'root' was already decided in the corrupted opening stretch, so the real structure ends up as dead code the compiler drops. At margin=2, the SAME frame_depth==0 candidate-vs-slot competition is legal at the same position 1, and the bias does win its own local before/after comparison there too -- but the downstream semantic_plan_root_margin_decode_weight=2 / semantic_plan_root_decode_weight=8 biases (fixed, active in every arm, applied later in the same per-position bias stack) push the score back above the floored slot token before the position's final argmax is taken, so the emitted token is still the real component.",
    "is_it_scope_leak_or_weak_base_logits": "Neither exactly as E626 framed the question. The bias never adds score to a non-slot candidate -- it is exactly as narrowly scoped as designed. The leak is that the grammar itself makes a bare slot token a legal substitute for opening a component at the same decode position, and which one wins is a magnitude race against the downstream semantic_plan_root* correction biases, decided purely by whether required_slot_margin_decode_weight exceeds their combined effect -- not by base-logit strength and not by any scoping gap in _required_slot_margin_bias itself.",
    "bias_stack_order_relevant_here": [
      "schema_role_slot_bias",
